1. Chat on public home, not admin
Chat should be on the root home page (/), not the admin.
/ = public page with an inline chat in the middle (no popup).
Admin stays separate (e.g. no chat there, or only for testing).
2. Customers page and customer model
Customers page in admin: list everyone who has ever interacted with the bot.
Unique identifier: email.
Later: When Zendesk/other APIs are connected, sync and store customer data on this server (keyed by email).
Merge: If two people have the same name and address but different emails, support merging them into one canonical customer (one email, all conversations reassigned).
3. Website source: sync was “too fast”, 0 chunks
When website sync finishes with 0 chunks, treat it as a failure and show a clear error (don’t show success).
URL: If user enters a URL without https://, normalize it (e.g. add https://).
First page failure: If the first page fails to fetch, show that exact error (e.g. HTTP 403, timeout), not a generic message.
Timeout: Add a fetch timeout so the server doesn’t hang.
Admin: Show the full sync error message in the Data sources list when status is “Failed”.
4. Website behind Cloudflare (403)
Crawler was getting HTTP 403 from the site (e.g. mdttac.com).
Use browser-like request headers (User-Agent, Accept, etc.) so the site is less likely to block the crawler.
Support custom User-Agent via env (e.g. CRAWLER_USER_AGENT) so the same string can be allowed in Cloudflare WAF; crawler must send that User-Agent when set.
5. Home page chat: “nothing happens” on Send / Enter
On the public home page, clicking Send or pressing Enter did nothing.
CSP: Avoid relying on inline scripts; use an external script (e.g. chat.js) so strict CSP doesn’t block it.
Form / Enter: Use a form and handle submit so Enter reliably sends the message (and doesn’t reload the page).
Streaming: SSE stream from the API can arrive in chunks; buffer and parse by event (e.g. split on \n\n) so partial lines don’t break parsing and responses show up.
Backend: Serve the chat script (e.g. GET /chat.js).
6. Remove chat from admin home
Remove the chat box from the admin “home” (Conversations page).
Admin should list/manage conversations (and later customers, sources, etc.) without an inline chat there.
7. Crawl the whole website, not just 50/200 pages
Website source was limited to 50 then 200 pages; the site has hundreds of pages and should support thousands of chunks.
Increase limits: Much higher default and max for “max pages” (e.g. 500 default, up to 10,000 then 50,000).
Admin: Let user set “Max pages to crawl” when adding a website source, and edit this on the source detail page, then Sync again without re-adding the source.
Long pages: Split long page content into smaller chunks (e.g. ~2000 chars with overlap) so retrieval can use the right parts.
Retrieval: Retrieve more chunks per query (e.g. 14 instead of 8) so answers use more of the knowledge base.
8. Zendesk: how to know it’s working
Connections: Zendesk credentials (subdomain, email, API token) are in Admin → Connections.
Data source: User must add a “Zendesk Help Center” source in Data sources and Sync; then “View chunks” shows articles.
Sync status (success/failed) and error should be visible in the Data sources list.
9. Zendesk source: what to enter
When adding a Zendesk Help Center source, there is only one field: Name.
It’s a label for the source (e.g. “Zendesk Help”, “Help Center”).
Credentials and locale/defaults come from Connections and config, not from this form.
10. Zendesk sync failed / “fetch failed”
Sync can fail with “fetch failed” (network-level, e.g. wrong subdomain, DNS, or Railway outbound restrictions).
Subdomain must be only the part before .zendesk.com (e.g. mdt), not the full domain.
User should see the exact error in the Data sources list for debugging.
11. No limits on sources – get all data
Zendesk: No 200-article cap; sync all Help Center articles (e.g. default/max 10,000).
Website: Support up to tens of thousands of pages (e.g. max 50,000) so large sites can be fully crawled.
Google Drive: Paginate folder listing (don’t stop at first 200 files per folder); support deeper folder trees (e.g. depth 15).
Shopify: Already paginate through all products; keep “no limit” behavior.
Goal: all possible information from each source type gets into the database.
